data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous LINQ via an **opt-in** (`EnableSyncOverAsync`). In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. The Cosmos DB provider is now strictly async-only.

Every synchronous call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## The fix

Convert all sync methods to async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
- Callers up the chain must also be updated to `await` these methods

This isn't just a cosmetic change — the Cosmos DB SDK is natively async, so sync-over-async was always masking potential deadlocks and thread pool starvation. The .NET 11 removal forces the correct pattern.
